labextension: Extreme volume refactoring

* Introduce Clone Notebook Volume option
  This option is used to snapshot a volume currently mounted to the
  Notebook Server and feed the pipeline with a clone of that.
  Users select a volume using the mount point dropdown menu, which
  triggers an autofill. They, then, may modify volume's name or size.
* Introduce Clone Existing Snapshot option
  This option is similar to Create Empty Volume, but also has a fixed
  'rok/origin' annotation with a RokChooser button.
* Everytime the extension renders, get all Notebook Server volumes information
* Reorder volume name & mount point
* Make DefaultEmpty{Volume,Annotation} globals
* Initialize all state variables
* Integrate RokChooser in annotations when key is 'rok/origin'
* Use double volumes list for UX purposes
  * 'state.metadata.volumes' is the volumes list handled by Kale
  * 'state.volumes' may handle several volume types that Kale wouldn't
    need to. That way we can massively improve UX.
* Fix volume annotations bugs
* Add NB Volumes when opening a notebook

Styling stuff
* Make Add* and Remove* buttons pretty
* Add kale-component css class and modify other classes
* Make space between size & size type and annotation key & value
* Add bottom border to volume entries

Signed-off-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

backend: RPC: Add rpc.log.setup_logging()

This RPC is to be called as soon as possible. It should be called by the
frontend immediately right after 'kale' module existence check.
It sets up a logger that contains a StreamHandler and a FileHanlder. The
second saves its logs under '$HOME/kale.log' or './kale.log'

This logger also mutes the loggers 'urllib3' and 'kubernetes'.

function, because it needs to run in the same kernel with the open
notebook. Therefore, there isn't a request object to pass.

If we want to log something inside this RPC in the future, then we
should reconsider its arguments.

backend: Add, Update & Reorganize Dockerfiles (#41)

* Add Dockerfiles for NotebookServer images

* Dockerfile
  Build an image with the latest releases of Kale & JupyterLab Extension
* Dockerfile.rok
  Build an image with the latest releases of Kale & JypyterLab Extension
  on top of an image that contains Rok Client
* Dockerfile.dev
  Build an image with Kale & JupyterLab Extension built from source
  (defaults to 'master' branches)
* Dockerfile.rok.dev
  Build an image with Kale & JupyterLab Extension built from source
  (defaults to 'master' branches) that contains Rok Client

backend: Support pipeline metrics (#66)

* Parse pipeline-metrics cell tag

Extend the existing parse_notebook function to parse pipeline-metrics
tags. This tag is treated in a special way, very similarly to
pipeline-parameters. The only difference is that pipeline-metrics is
only allowed to be defined at the end of the notebook (enforced by
checking that no tag is found after detecting a pipeline-metrics tag)

* Implement func to parse a metrics code block

A metrics code blocks is a list of print statement, where the print
argument is just a variable name. In terms of python ast, the print
argument is an Expr node with a Name node as value. The code validates
lines of code in the form of `print(<name>)` and returns a list of
variable names

* Extend templates to generate pipeline metrics code

Introduce a new template that generates code that is resposnsible for
saving metrics to mlpipeline-metrics.json and extend the existing
pipeline template to add that file to the task responsible to output
metrics

* Fix pipeline parameters parsing

Fix regression introduced in a previous PR:
https://github.com/kubeflow-kale/kale/pull/61

The function get_pipeline_parameters_source would include in the
pipeline-parameters source any code cell with reserved names (different
from skip or step). This fix (correclty) ignore any tag that is included
in the _TAGS_LANGUAGE const.

* Add rpc function to get pipeline metrics

In order to get the list of pipeline metrics, the rpc function needs to
get the complete source of all the pipeline metrics cells.
To simplify the code in parser.py, common code between
get_pipeline_parameters_source and get_pipeline_parameters_source
is moved to _get_reserved_tag_source and generalized.

* Add new unit tests

* Add local e2e test

Update existing e2e test and add a new one from a local notebook to
tests both pipeline parameters and pipeline metrics

backend: Improve dependencies detection algorithm (#83)

* Fix a regression introduced in #81

During the detection of all the candidates to be marshalled from a step,
functions and classes were skipped. In this way steps could not marshal
functions or classes. This commit fixes that.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>

* Rename variable to avoid potential conflicts

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>

* Save node's graph info at the end of iteration

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>

* Search for chained deps inside fns with free vars

Functions can be dependent on variables outside of the scope the
function body (free variables). These free variables can be themselves
functions that in turn use other free variables. This chain of
dependecies can be arbitrary long. This commit covers this case by
iteratively searching for the available functions in a step.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>

* Update tests

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>

* Correct parsing of functions with a return stmt

By parsing the function def statement first and just then parsing the
body detecting the missing name with pyflakes, the report would not
detect missing names on the `return` line, becase the report would just
say that it was outside of a function.

This commit solves that, by simplifying how functions are parsed, since
having individual arguments was not needed anyway.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>
Reviewed-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

backend: Produce metrics from specific steps (#95)

* Compute leaf nodes in graph_utils

Since the computation of the leaf nodes was done the same way in three
different parts of the codebase, this commits adds a function to utils
to do just that. Moreover, now all nodes that don't even have an
in-degree (i.e. are single nodes 'outside' the graph) are not taken into
consideration.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>

* Assign metrics to specific steps

Instead of creating an additional pipeline step just for generating a
/mlpipeline-metrics.json file to output metrics, we add a function to
'assign' to specific pipeline steps the output of metrics, based on

backend: Add RPCs and helpers to manage Katib experiments (#103)

* Add utils to create, watch and collect metrics of a KFP run

This commits introduces some helper functions to create and monitor KFP
runs and retrieve metrics produced by a run. These helpers are used by
the Katb-KFP shim in the Katib Trials.

* Add Katib RPC module

Introduce Katib RPC functions and helpers used to create and monitor
Katib experiments. Specifically:

- create_katib_experiment: Receives as input a (KFP) pipeline id and the
kale notebook metadata and creates a Katib Experiment CR that is then
submitted to the K8s API server.
- get_experiment: Given an experiment name and a namespace this function
returns the status of the matching experiment. This function is used by
the labextension to monitor the state of the Katib run.

* Add get_experiment and create_experiment RPCs

Since Katib creates a bunch of KFP pipeline runs every time, we create
an ad-hoc KFP experiment for every new Katib experiment, where all the
related KFP runs end up.

These RPCs are used by the labextension to create and get a new
experiment when using Katib.

* Validate katib metadata

* Add dockerfiles for katib trial image

Katib trials run with our Katib-KFP shim, that just needs Kale to be
installed. These light weight Dockerfile help with that.

Add annotation and limit tags and GPU UI (#101)

* backend: Parse cell annotations and limits tags

Add 2 new tags to the Kale tags:

- limit: these tags specify K8s resource limits to be applied to a
step's pod. The syntax is `limit:<limit_key>:<limit_value>`.
- annotation: these tags work similarly to `limit`, but specify
annotations to be applied to the step's pod.

These tags are expected in the notebook cells metadata, alongside the
`step` and `prev` tags. Moreover, they are expected just in a cell that
also has a `step` tag. This is will be true in general, since the UI
will enforce this behavior.

* backend: Set limits and annotations to ContainerOp

Use the KFP SDK to add annotations and limits to the steps.

* labextension: Add a cell metadata dialog

Introduce a new dialog to set GPU limits to steps. This dialog is just a
first iteration of what will be a richer form to add any sort of K8s
resource limits, annotations and other useful information to compile the
pipeline.

The implementation is pretty much specific to GPU field, but will be
reworked to be more dynamic in the future.

* labextension: Handle limit tags in TagsUtils

* labextension: Add an inline limit tags summary

This implementation is specific for GPU resource limits, as this is the
only kind of limit that is supported. As more limits and cell tags are
added, the generation of this summary will be refactored to be more
dynamic.

labextension: Add components to define, run and monitor Katib experiments (#104)

* Add Katib metadata interfaces

* Add a dialog component to update Katib metadata

This commit introduces a Dialog component that exposes all the Katib
metadata. When it is loaded, the component sends an RPC to get the
current notebook's pipeline parameters and metrics. In this way the user
can dynamically select which parameters to use for the Katib Experiment
and which metric for the goal.

The notebook's Katib metadata is updated when the dialog is closed.

* Run Katib when clicking on run button

Clicking on the run button with Katib mode enabled will trigger an RPC
to create a Katib Experiment. The deploy progress UI monitors the
creation of the Experiment CR and the lifecycle of the Katib Trials.

Since a single Katib experiment comprises multiple KFP pipelines runs,
we create a new experient name as <exp-name>-<rnd-str> for every Katib
run. In this way, all the KFP runs of a specific Katib experiemnt are
grouped together and we don't have name conflicts.

* Ask to save notebook on Katib dialog open

The Katit Dialog, when opening, sends an RPC to read the current
notebook and get the pipeline parameters and metrics. So the notebook
needs to be saved to its newest version. We want to make sure the user
knows what is happening and does not save unwanted changes

labextension: Add lists to numeric Katib args (#109)

* Add lists in numeric Katib args

Katib support categorical arguments (i.e. lists of values) or numeric
arguments (int, double) defined in terms of `min`, `max` and `step`. It
is often the case that we need to run HP Tuning with a numeric arg that
has a list of choices (e.g. 0.0001, 0.001, 0.1) not expressible as a
range.

We allow changing the default range spec of numeric pipeline args to
categorical. This works because KFP converts all the pipeline args
from string to their annotated type.

There could be unintended side effects in how Katib's optimisation
algorithms handle categorical differently from range. For that we
inform the user when making this choice.

labextension: Improve active cell tracking (#125)

This commits changes in how the extension tracks the currently active
notebook cell. Tracking this information is needed because we are
showing just one cell metadata editor at any given time.

Since the beginning, this information was tracked in the state of the
LeftPanelWidget component and was then passed down to the InlineMetadata
component. Since the LeftPanelWidget just acted as a tracker, without
actively using this information, now the tracking is moved to
InlineMetadata so that there is no useless state passing.

In this way, many functions inside LeftPanelWidget are freed from having
to set the state, and can now be refactored more easily.

backend: Handle exiting from IPython gracefully

Running the function `sys.exit()` raises a special exception `SystemExit`
that is not caught by the python REPL, making it exit the program.
IPython's REPL, instead, does catch `SystemExit`. It displays the message
and then goes back to the REPL.

Code that could either run in an IPython kernel (because the Kale pipeline
was produced from a notebook) or in a standard Python process, needs to
handle the exit process seamlessly, regardless of where it's running.

If a Kale function wants to terminate the Python process and it could be
running either inside IPython or a standard Python process, then it
should use `utils.graceful_exit`. In case the code is running inside
inside IPython, `graceful_exit` will raise a `KaleGracefulExit`
exception that is expected to be captured by
`kale.utils.jupyter_utils.capture_streams`.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>
Reviewed-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

logging: Add support for logging empty lines

Using a standard logger, it's not possible to just print empty lines
without having to print the Formatter prefix as well. This can be a
limitation when we want to use just the logger for user-facing outputs,
but we also want to be able to space out some section, producing empty
lines.

This commit extends the base Logger class with a method that, when
called, it temporarily suppress all the handlers' formatters with the
empty string, logs empty lines, and then restores the original
formatters.

NOTE: This function is not thread safe. If multiple processes are using
the same logger concurrently, there might be cases when one thread uses
the logger while its formatters are being suppressed by another thread.
Currently, Kale is not multithreaded, so this is not an issue.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>
Reviewed-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

Support Jupyter notebook-dir CLI argument

Jupyterlab can be started with the `--notebook-dir` CLI argument. The
specified dir will effectively become the root path visible from the JP
UI. This could be useful if one wants to start the Jupyter server in the
home folder, but wants to give access to the user just to a subfolder.

Until now Kale was assuming that the jupyter process was running in the
HOME directory, without `--notebook-dir`. When this assumption does not
hold anymore, Kale cannot find the notebook anymore, since we use a
relative path.

This commit retrieves the "server root" path (i.e. the absolute path to
`--notebook-dir`) and uses it to always point to the notebook with an
absolute path.

NOTE: `PageConfig.getOption('serverRoot')` returns a path where the HOME
prefix is `~`. We handle this in the backend by expanding the path using
`os.path.expanduser`

backend: Refactor into components

This commit overhauls how Kale converts notebooks into KFP DSL. The main
idea is to refactor the loosely-coupled functions into objects that
provide an extensible API and better abstraction.

Until now, the rough journey a notebook would take to be converted to
the output KFP code would be:

0. Validate the notebook metadata using the metadatautils module
1. Use the nbparser package to convert the notebook to a nx.DiGraph
object
2. Store every step's attribute using nx's steps attributes
3. Detect the dependencies between the steps using the static_analysis
package
4. Generate the DSL code using the codegen package.

The nx graph object would be passed by references among all of these
functions and no object (apart from the main Kale class) would track
some state.

This commit refactors most of the above into the following objects:

* Pipeline: wraps nx.DriGraph, to provide a higher level API and
simplify several pipeline/graph-related operations throughout the code.
* Step: provide an object oriented way to store and access pipeline
steps attributes, instead of having to deal with nx's dict-like step
attributes.
* Config: implements a general purpose configuration container, for
defining and validating configurations. This is mostly meant to replace
the metadatautils module, to easily enforce typed configurations across
objects and provide complex validation functions.
* NotebookProcessor: this is mostly a refactor of the nbparser package
into a self-contained class that exploits the Pipeline object directly.
The most interesting new function is `to_pipeline`, which imitate the
origin Kale.notebook_to_graph function. The processor is also supposed
to provide a ready-to-use pipeline object, ready to be compiled to DSL
without needed additional processing or context.
* Compiler: this object mainly refactors parts of the now defunct
codegen package. The compiler take a pipeline (produced by a processor)
and renders it to KFP DSL.

The interaction between the objects described is roughly as follows:

              +----------+
              | Notebook |
              +----+-----+
                   |
            +------+------+     +----------------+
            | NBProcessor +-----+ NotebookConfig |
            +------+------+     +--------+-------+
                   |                     |
              +----+-----+        +------+-----+
              | Pipeline |        | Validators |
              +----+-----+        +------------+
                   |
              +----+-----+
              | Compiler |
              +----+-----+
                   |
              +----+----+
              | KFP DSL |
              +---------+

Take a look at how the e2e tests are being refactored in the subsequent
commits as well.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>
Reviewed-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

marshal: Refactor backend with class components

This commit overhauls the marshal package introducing a new class-based
backend system that is easier to maintain and extend. A list of changes
follows:

* New MarshalBackend based class which provides common functionality
  for any marshalling backend. This class implements two public
  functions `save` and `load`. These functions use `dill` to marshal
  objects and are the replacement of the previous `resource_save_all`
  and `resource_load_all` functions. Refer to the class docstring for
  details on how to subclass.

* A series of backends which subclass MarshalBackend.

* A new Dispatcher class which brings together the functionality of both
  PatternDispatcher and TypeDispatcher. This new dispatcher will return
  MarshalBackend instances, instead of just functions.

* Custom backends register to Dispatcher in a similar way as before,
  a decorator.

* The `utils` module is refactored into Dispatcher functions. The main
  `save` and `load` APIs are exposed at the package level using
  `__init__.py`. This is the main API that external code should care
  about.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>
Reviewed-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

marshal: Remove custom exception handling

The custom exception KaleMarshalException was created to catch both
known and unknown exceptions during the marshalling process, providing
the end-users with reasonable messages and not expose the internal
tracebacks.

Having such custom exceptions makes a lot of sense if they are passed to
"upper" levels in the call chain to be dealt with. But in our case, we
were just raising and then catching these custom exception within the
same class (`Dispatcher`) thus invalidating the benefit of having such
custom Exception class.

This commit removes the custom exception while still exposing error to
the user in a user-friendly way and simplify a lot the Dispatcher code.

backend: Introduce serveutils

This commit introduces new functionality to interact with KFServing,
create InferenceService CRs, get and parse them, and hit prediction
endpoints.

The standout function/classes introduced in this utils module are:

1. The `serve` function

This function is the end-user's only visible API. It automates the
process of creating and submitting a new InferenceService CR just by
passing a model object.

`serve` makes use of Kale's marshalling mechanism to understand the type
of the object and produce the correct predictor accordingly.

The integration with a snapshotting mechanism is essential, as `serve`
takes a snapshot of the PVC containing the marshalled model and uses
this snapshot to mount a new PVC on the new InferenceService's
predictor.

Checkout `serve`'s docstring for more details about the series of steps
that the function takes to automate the entire process.

2. KFServer class

This class acts as a wrapper around an InferenceService CR, as deployed
by the `serve` function. `serve` returns an instance of `KFServer` which
can be used by the end-user to inspect various attributed of the
InferenceService, delete it, or hit the prediction endpoint just by
calling a function (`.predict`), without having to awkwardly send HTTP
requests.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>
Reviewed-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

kfserving: Introduce transformer package

This commit introduces a new package that is used as an entrypoint for a
Kale-deployed InferenceService's transformer.

Notable actions taken by the KaleTransformer class:

* Load the transformer function, pickled by the `serve` function of the
  `serveutils` module.
* Monkey patch the pickled function to change its scope to the current
  module
* Read the original notebook and execute the global cells, to resolve
  potential import statements of the processing function
* Load all processing artifacts
* Run the processing function on the provided data when the user hits
  the transformer with a request

Implementing the entrypoint in the `__main__` module allows us to run
`python -m kale.kfserving` as the entrypoint of the transformer
container.

marshal: Allow a backend to exit on missing lib

The default behavior of marshal backends is to try to pickle an object
with dill in case the specialized library of a custom backend is not
resolved. This is done to cover some (potential) cases when the object
can still be marshalled using `dill`.

In the case of SKLearn object, we don't want this fallback to happen
because SKLearn object **can** be saved with `dill` (`pickle`), so if the
user didn't install `joblib` (which is not a dependency of `sklearn`,
they would end up saving the model with `pickle`.

This poses a problem for when the marshal backend is used for serving,
since KFServing requires SKLearn object to be saved with `joblib`.

This commit thus introduces a general way for custom backend to opt out
from this default fallback, and applied it to the SKLearn backned.

Signed-off-by: Stefano Fioravanzo <stefano@arrikto.com>
Reviewed-by: Ilias Katsakioris <elikatsis@arrikto.com>

backend: Fix pip 20.3 dependency resolution

With the new dependency resolver introduced in pip 20.3, dependency
resolution would get stuck because of the following conflicts:

1. `kfserving` requires `kubernetes==10.0.1`
2. Kale's `setup.py` specifies `kubernetes>=11.0.0`

We introduced (2) in [1]. This commit reverts that change and manually
catches the `TypeError` exception.

`kfserving` version 0.5.0 changes the `kubernetes` requirement to
install versions >=12.0.0. However, this is incompatible with KFP
requirement (<12.0.0).
This is also incompatible with our code, since in version 12.0.0 there
are breaking changes on code we import (e.g., Exceptions).

As a result, we change the restrictions as follows:
* `kfserving >= 0.4.0, < 0.5.0`
* `kubernetes < 12.0.0`

Closes https://github.com/kubeflow-kale/kale/issues/273
Closes https://github.com/kubeflow-kale/kale/issues/275

[1] https://github.com/kubeflow-kale/kale/commit/e3bc079a6e971e42b02aa04fcfaceb4ea28faf31

docker: Fix Dockerfiles (enum & KFP installation)

  on KFP installation, this happens since KFP version 1.1.0. The faulty
  dependency is docstring-parser [*]
* Do not install KFP separately, let Kale requirements do it

[*] `enum34` patches the built-in Enum and is known to cause issues with
many libraries. In general, the solution is to just uninstall it. Most
probably this dependency is needed by the base image's TensorFlow, thus
we just pin it to a version that work with KFP as well.

Closes https://github.com/kubeflow-kale/kale/issues/274

sdk: Introduce a Kale SDK

This commit introduces a first iteration of a Kale SDK, useful for
converting plain Python functions into a KFP pipeline.

The @step and @pipeline decorators implemented in sdk/api.py can be used
to decorate, respectively, functions that will be converted to pipeline
steps and a function which orchestrated the execution of the former.

A @pipeline function cannot contain any arbitrary Python code, as it
needs to statically parsed to build the resulting pipeline.

The new PythonProcessor is responsible for parsing the decorated
functions into a Pipeline object and the new function template renders
a step accordingly.

Lastly, the Marshaller class (marshal/decorator.py) is essential to
execute the original function while still marshalling variables from/to
disk using Kale's marshalling backends.

backend: Improve base docker image detection

Just reading the Pod spec's container image is not enough to have a
reproducible reference to the current image, because an image tag can be
re-assigned to newer builds, in the future (e.g. when using the `latest`
tag). The only way to have reproducible reference is by using the
image manifest's `sha`.

Kubernetes exposes this in the Pod's `status`, under `containerStatuses`
[1], in the field `imageID`. In the case this field is empty (this could
happen when the image was built locally), then fallback to reading the
Pod's container `image` field.

[1] https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/generated/kubernetes-api/v1.20/#containerstatus-v1-core  # noqa: 501

backend: Upload and run pipelines with versions

KFP provides the APIs to upload pipeline versions. Each pipeline has a
`name` and an `id` and has a list of versions, each one with its own
`name` and `id` (unique across all KFP versions - not just within the
context of the pipeline).

Note: Since KFP does not provide a way to name the first version of a
pipeline, when uploading one for the first time we do the following:

1. Upload pipeline. This also generates a new version with the same name
as the pipeline
2. Create a new version with a Kale autogenerated hash
3. Delete the first, autogenerated, version

sdk: Add artifact decorator

This commit introduces a new SDK decorator that allows users to declare
the artifacts created during a step execution. The `@artifact` decorator
is thus supposed to be used on functions that have already been
decorated with the `@step` decorator.

Declaring step artifacts must be done before the step actually executes,
because Kale needs to create a pipeline that is aware of these outputs,
and properly update each step's output artifacts dictionary in the KFP
DSL.

Currently only HTML artifacts are supported.

katib: Support both v1beta1 and v1alpha3

This commit brings back the support for v1alpha3 using katibutils and
introduces dynamic discovery of Katib version.

Kale attempts to list Katib v1beta1 Experiments. If it succeeds or it
raises a 403 (Forbidden) ApiException, then the v1beta1 CRDs are
installed in the cluster.
In this case, Kale will continue with apiVersion v1beta1.

If listing Katib v1beta1 Experiments fails, Kale will continue with
apiVersion v1alpha3.
NOTE: Kale does not check whether Katib v1alpha3 is actually installed.
